snippet.textDisplay:
Either way the court decision goes, Australian govt shot itself in the foot big time and Djokovic is already a winner. 
If the court decides to go govt way - the Australian judicial system observed humiliation by the political power and as time goes by, this truth will stand on its own even more convincingly. 
If the court decides to go Djokovic's way - the Australian judicial system preserved its integrity, but the govt will be outed as capricious, opportunistic, tyrannical and worst - incompetent. 
Simply, there's no good outcome for Australia in this one. 
Morrisson govt can forget the next elections and Morrisson personally can forget his political career, that includes all of the ministers that got directly involved and exposed along his side. The mess that they've created, due to their political opportunism is just too much to forget and it's going to stain Australia for a time to come. 
It's a complete "fiasco down under". 

At this point - Djokovic, regardless of how this ends, can not lose. He might win and win epically. But he cannot lose. 
He stood his ground, defended his beliefs and didn't cave to whims and capriciousness (and even humiliation and torture)  of the tyrannical political power - he stood alone, in a foreign, hostile country and he prevailed. Untouched.  
If he wins the court again - his legacy will not be just the GOAT of tennis anymore, but much bigger and more important legacy of courage, freedom and honor. 
Furthermore, given that Serbian govt will be forced to get out of any negotiations with "Rio Tinto" and stop their mining (and ecological disaster) plans/projects - as public outcry was already strong even before this, -- this will further cement Djokovic's almost "heroic" status in his home country. 
BTW - Morrisson, as I understand, has HUGE personal financial interest and exposure in "Rio Tinto" - and this will certainly not bode well with his fellow shareholders and the board.  

Djokovic, regardless of how he feels right now, and that cannot be very good - and regardless of how this end, when he's able to put some distance in between will know that these few weeks were well worth it and well spent.
